  "output": "I have enough context now — this is a Python async job-scraper CLI (114 configured ATS sources, SQLite-backed dedup), not a web/React app. I'll frame the analysis accordingly.\n\n## Codebase context\n\nThis is `jobsquare`, an async Python pipeline: `fetchers.py` (httpx, 15 ATS integrations, 114 configured sources) → `filters.py` → `store.py` (SQLite dedup) → `notify.py`. **There is no React/frontend code** — the \"unnecessary re-renders\" section is N/A; I've substituted the closest applicable equivalent (redundant per-item work in hot loops).\n\n---\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (highest impact)\n\n`Store.diff()` runs one `SELECT` per job, in a Python loop, for every job fetched that run:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    ...\n```\n\nWith 114 sources — several of them big boards (Amazon/Microsoft/Google/Netflix run to thousands of postings each) — a single pipeline run can push this into the thousands of individual round-trips. Even against local SQLite, each `execute()` re-enters the SQLite VM; that adds up and this function also holds the write path (`_insert`/`_update`), so it's on the critical path of every run.\n\n**Fix** — load the whole key→hash map once, diff in memory:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    new, changed, unchanged_keys = [], [], []\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n\n    existing = {r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"]\n                for r in cur.execute(\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs\")}\n\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = job.content_hash                       # compute once (see #3)\n        prev = existing.get(job.key)\n        if prev is None:\n            new.append(job)\n            self._insert(cur, job, now, h)\n        elif prev != h:\n            changed.append(job)\n            self._update(cur, job, now, h)\n        else:\n            unchanged_keys.append(job.key)\n\n    cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\",\n                     [(now, k) for k in unchanged_keys])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(N) SELECTs into 1, and batches the (usually largest) \"unchanged, just bump last_seen\" group into a single `executemany`.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Redundant computation — regex recompiled per job — `filters.py:11-42`\n\n`match()` is called once per job by `filter_jobs()`, and it calls `_compile(exclude)` / `_compile(include)` **inside** itself — so the same include/exclude keyword patterns get `re.compile`'d fresh for every single job in the batch, not once for the run.\n\n```python\ndef match(job: Job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    ...\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):   # recompiled every call\n```\n\n**Fix** — compile once in `filter_jobs`, pass compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef match(job: Job, *, include: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          exclude: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          locations: list[str] | None = None,   # pre-lowered\n          cutoff: datetime | None = None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    if locations:\n        loc = job.location.lower()\n        if not any(l in loc for l in locations):\n            return False\n    if cutoff is not None:\n        dt = job.posted_dt\n        if dt is not None and dt < cutoff:\n            return False\n    return True\n\n\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = None\n    if rules.get(\"max_age_days\"):\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(rules[\"max_age_days\"]))\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = [l.lower() for l in (rules.get(\"locations\") or [])]\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\nThis is O(N·K) regex compiles collapsed to O(K), where K = number of keyword rules.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Redundant computation — `content_hash` hashed twice per job — `models.py:66-69`, `store.py:67,77,89`\n\n`Job.content_hash` is a plain `@property` (sha256 over a joined string) with no memoization. In `diff()`, it's evaluated once for the comparison (`row[\"content_hash\"] != job.content_hash`) and again inside `_insert`/`_update` via `to_row()`. That's 2× the sha256 calls needed. Fixed above in #1's rewrite by computing `h = job.content_hash` once and threading it through — cheap but free once you're already touching `diff()`.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Caching opportunity — notifier HTTP calls open a fresh connection each time — `notify.py:46,56,93-97`\n\n`notify_slack`, `notify_webhook`, and `notify_sms` each call the module-level `httpx.post(...)`, which spins up and tears down a whole `Client` (TCP+TLS handshake) per call. Low-impact today (≤3 calls per run), but if notification volume ever grows (e.g. per-job webhook fan-out instead of one batched call), switch to one shared `httpx.Client` for connection pooling:\n\n```python\n_client = httpx.Client(timeout=15)   # module-level, reused across notifiers\n```\n\nNot urgent — flagging as future-proofing, not a current bottleneck.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Memory leaks — none found\n\nResource hygiene here is actually solid:\n- `Store` is always used via `with Store(...) as store:` (`pipeline.py:42`, `agent.py:73,126`) — connection closed properly.\n- `fetch_all` (`fetchers.py:770-787`) creates its `httpx.AsyncClient` and closes it in a `try/finally`, and correctly skips closing when a caller-supplied client is passed in (`owns_client` guard).\n- `smtplib.SMTP` in `notify_email` uses a `with` block.\n- `cmd_pdf_render` (`agent.py:219-228`) cleans up its temp file in `finally`.\n\nThe one non-runtime observation: `output/` and `reports/` accumulate CV/report artifacts indefinitely with no pruning — that's disk growth, not a memory leak, and likely intentional (these are the user-facing deliverables), so I'm not flagging it as a defect.\n\n---\n\n### 6. Design note — sequential pagination (not a bug, just a ceiling)\n\nPer-source fetchers like `fetch_amazon`/`fetch_microsoft`/`fetch_google`/`fetch_netflix`/`fetch_twosigma`/`fetch_optiver` paginate with a sequential `for page in range(max_pages): await ...` loop, since each page's continuation depends on whether the previous page returned fresh results. This is correct but means a single big board (e.g. Amazon at `max_pages=40`) is bottlenecked by its own round-trip latency × page count regardless of the `concurrency=8` cross-source semaphore in `fetch_all`. Not worth restructuring unless run time becomes a problem — flagging only so it's not mistaken for an oversight.\n\n---\n\n## Priority order\n1. **`store.diff()` N+1 → batch SELECT** (biggest win, scales with total jobs fetched: thousands/run across 114 sources)\n2. **`filters.py` regex recompilation** (scales with jobs × keyword rules — cheap fix, real waste)\n3. Dedupe the double `content_hash` computation (free while touching #1)\n4. Notifier connection reuse (low priority, future-proofing only)\n",
